By the end it got even harder! At first it wasn't so bad.
The sequence was hard. it would have been easier to get them all at once. I am a visual learner and so having them in the same place on the screen was extra hard and one at a time as well.
THE NARRATOR WAS POOR GROWING UP UNTIL HIS DAD GOT A JOB KEEPING THE WASHINGTON HEIGHTS LIBRARY CLEAN.
HE THEN HAD ACCESS TO A WORLD OF OPPORTUNITY BECAUSE HE HAD BOOKS EVERYWHERE.
HE READ A TON AND DEVELOPED A LOVE OF LEARNING THAT HELPED HIM BE THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL AND GO ON TO COLLEGE.
HE WAS A PROFESSOR AFTER HE GRADUATED.
HE HAD A SWEET, BUT INTENSE, MOMENT WHEN HE SHOWED HIS DAD HIS CLASSROOM.
HIS DAD WAS PROUD OF HIS WORK AND CLEANED THE SHELVES AND FLOORS UNTIL THEY GLEAMED.
HE EVEN CLEANED THE TOPS OF THE SHELVES.
CUSTODIANS LIVING IN THE LIBRARY THEY TENDED WAS COMMON IN THE 1940S, BUT THE NARRATOR STILL FELT LIKE HE WAS A LITTLE WEIRD.
HE NEVER BROUGHT FRIENDS HOME BECAUSE HE DIDN'T WANT TO BE DIFFERENT.
WHEN THE LIBRARY WAS OPEN, HE HAD TO BE QUIET, BUT WHEN IT CLOSED HE HAD THE RUN OF THE PLACE AND COULD READ WHATEVER HE WANTED WHENEVER HE WANTED.
BOOKS HELPED HIM SEE FURTHER THAN HIS DAD HAD, WHICH WAS HIS DAD'S GOAL THE WHOLE TIME.
IN THE 1940S NYC LIBRARIES HAD THEIR CUSTODIANS LIVING IN THE LIBRARIES.
THE NARRATOR'S FAMILY WAS POOR, EVEN THOUGH HE THOUGHT HE WAS RICH. HIS DAD GOT A JOB WORKING AT THE WASHINGTON HEIGHTS LIBRARY, SO THE FAMILY MOVED IN.
HE THOUGHT IT WAS WEIRD, AND DIDN'T INVITE FRIENDS OVER FROM SCHOOL, BECAUSE HE WANTED TO BE LIKE EVERYONE ELSE. BUT AS HE GREW OLDER, IT BECAME MORE OF AN ASSET.
HE HAD TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAY, BUT AFTER THE LIBRARY CLOSED HE GOT TO RUN AND PLAY.
HE COULD READ WHATEVER HE WANTED, AND HE READ ALL KINDS OF THINGS. HE COULD EVEN WAKE UP AT 3AM TO CHECK A FACT IF HE NEEDED.
THIS LOVE OF LEARNING TOOK HIM ALL THE WAY THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL AND HE WAS THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL. HE THEN WENT TO COLLEGE AND AFTER GRADUATING HE GOT A JOB TEACHING.
HE GOT TO SHOW HIS DAD HIS CLASSROOM AND THE PLAQUE THAT SAID HIS NAME ON IT. HIS DAD WAS QUIET BUT CLEARLY PROUD.
HIS DAD KEPT THEIR LIBRARY CLEAN AND SHINED EVERYTHING UNTIL IT SPARKLED.
HE EVEN SHINED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
